2 Only for LB

2.1 Data visualisation & Hypotheses

We include only the data for strains isolated from the LB baker and from backsloppings T1 and T32, but not T5 for which there is only one

data_phenot_parms_clean_LB <- data_phenot_parms_clean %>%
  filter(parameter != "cell_t0",
         grepl("^LB", strain_name),
         !grepl("-T5-", strain_name)) %>%
  mutate(flour_id = strains$flour_id[match(strain_name, strains$strain_name)],
         baker_id = strains$baker_id[match(strain_name, strains$strain_name)],
         flour_type = flours$mill_type[match(flour_id, flours$flour_id)],
         backslopping = strains$backslopping[match(strain_name, 
                                                   strains$strain_name)],
         bs_time = backsloppings$bs_time[match(interaction(backslopping, baker_id),
                                               interaction(backsloppings$backslopping,
                                                           backsloppings$baker_id))],
         cell_t0 = data_cyto$cell_t0[match(robot_id, data_cyto$robot_id)]) %>%
  filter(!if_any(everything(), ~ is.na(.x)))
ggplot(data_phenot_parms_clean_LB) +
  aes(x = backslopping, y = value, fill = paste(flour_type, bloc_month)) +
  geom_boxplot(varwidth = T) +
  facet_wrap(~ parameter, scales = "free") +
  theme_minimal()

2.2 Formulation du modÃ¨le

Variable continue en effet alÃ©atoire > NON (https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/105698/how-do-i-enter-a-continuous-variable-as-a-random-effect-in-a-linear-mixed-effect)

La variable \(cell_{t_0}\) nâa pas sens comme effet alÃ©atoire.

The complete model is defined as follow :

phenotype ~ backslopping + flour_type + backslopping:flour_type + (1|strain_name) + (1|bloc_month)
model_LB <- "value ~ backslopping + flour_type + backslopping:flour_type + (1|strain_name) + (1|bloc_month)"

2.3 Model fitting

fits <- data_phenot_parms_clean_LB %>%
  group_by(parameter) %>%
  nest() %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(fit = list(lmer(formula = as.formula(model_LB), data = data, REML = T)),
         anova = list(anova(fit)))


for(i in 1:nrow(fits)) {
  
  cat("Parameter :", fits$parameter[[i]], "\n")
  cat("Model :", fits$model[[i]], "\n")
  cat(capture.output(fits$anova[[i]]), sep = "\n")
  cat("\n-----\n")
  
}

3 For LB and MB

3.1 Data visualisation & Hypotheses

We include only the data for strains isolated from the LB and MB baker and from backsloppings T1 and T32, but not T5 for which there are three strains :

table(strains$baker_id, strains$backslopping)
##      
##       T1 T5 T32
##   AM   3 11   0
##   LB  20  3  24
##   MB   7  0  21
##   PDC  1  0   1
data_phenot_parms_clean_LBMB <- data_phenot_parms_clean %>%
  filter(parameter != "cell_t0",
         grepl("(^LB)|(^MB)", strain_name),
         !grepl("-T5-", strain_name)) %>%
  mutate(flour_id = strains$flour_id[match(strain_name, strains$strain_name)],
         baker_id = strains$baker_id[match(strain_name, strains$strain_name)],
         flour_type = flours$mill_type[match(flour_id, flours$flour_id)],
         backslopping = strains$backslopping[match(strain_name, 
                                                   strains$strain_name)],
         bs_time = backsloppings$bs_time[match(interaction(backslopping, baker_id),
                                               interaction(backsloppings$backslopping,
                                                           backsloppings$baker_id))],
         cell_t0 = data_cyto$cell_t0[match(robot_id, data_cyto$robot_id)]) %>%
  filter(!if_any(everything(), ~ is.na(.x)))
param_tex <- c(
  lag = TeX(r"($t_{1g}$)", italic = T),
  co2max = TeX(r"($P_{max}$)", italic = T),
  vmax = TeX(r"($V_{max}$)", italic = T),
  tvmax = TeX(r"($t_{V_{max}}$)", italic = T),
  npop = TeX(r"($N_{pop}$)", italic = T),
  pdead = TeX(r"($p_{dead}$)", italic = T)) %>% 
  map_chr(deparse)

data_phenot_parms_clean_LBMB %>%
  mutate(parameter = param_tex[parameter]) %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = paste0(baker_id, "\n(bloc ", 
                 bloc_month, ")"), 
      y = value, fill = paste0(backslopping, " / ", flour_type)) +
  geom_boxplot(varwidth = T, 
               position = "dodge",
               width = 1.4) +
  facet_wrap(~ parameter, scales = "free", 
             labeller = label_parsed) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(wesanderson::wes_palette("Darjeeling1"),"blue","green")) +
  labs(fill = "Temps d'Ã©volution / Type de farine = ", 
       x = "Fournil\n(bloc expÃ©rimental)", y = "") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.justification = "left",
        legend.position = "bottom", 
        strip.background = element_rect(fill = "gray20"),
        strip.text = element_text(color = "white"),
        panel.spacing = unit(1.5, "lines"),

3.2 Formulation du modÃ¨le

The complete model is defined as follow :

model_LBMB <- "value ~ backslopping + baker_id + baker_id:backslopping + backslopping:flour_type + (1 | bloc_month) + (1 | strain_name)"

3.3 Model fitting and Assumptions testing

fits <- data_phenot_parms_clean_LBMB %>%
  mutate(value = ifelse(parameter == "npop", log(value), value)) %>%
  group_by(parameter) %>%
  nest() %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(fit = list(lmer(formula = as.formula(model_LBMB), 
                         data = data, REML = T)),
         anova = list(anova(fit)),
         homosc = list(anova(lm(abs(residuals(fit))^2 ~ strain_name + bloc_month,
                                data=data))),
         normres = list(shapiro.test(residuals(fit))))

data_phenot_parms_clean_ALL <- data_phenot_parms_clean %>%
  filter(parameter != "cell_t0") %>%
  mutate(flour_id = strains$flour_id[match(strain_name, strains$strain_name)],
         baker_id = strains$baker_id[match(strain_name, strains$strain_name)],
         flour_type = flours$mill_type[match(flour_id, flours$flour_id)],
         backslopping = strains$backslopping[match(strain_name, 
                                                   strains$strain_name)],
         bs_time = backsloppings$bs_time[match(interaction(backslopping, baker_id),
                                               interaction(backsloppings$backslopping,
                                                           backsloppings$baker_id))],
         cell_t0 = data_cyto$cell_t0[match(robot_id, data_cyto$robot_id)]) %>%
  filter(!if_any(everything(), ~ is.na(.x)))
ggplot(data_phenot_parms_clean_ALL) +

  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~ parameter, scales = "free") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

4.2 Formulation du modÃ¨le

The complete model is defined as follow :

phenotype ~ backslopping + flour_type + bs_time:flour_type + (1|baker_id/strain_name) + (1|bloc_month)
model_ALL <- "value ~ baker_id + bs_time + flour_type + bs_time:baker_id + bs_time:flour_type + (1|strain_name) + (1|bloc_month)"

4.3 Model fitting

fits <- data_phenot_parms_clean_ALL %>%
  group_by(parameter) %>%
  nest() %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(fit = list(lmer(formula = as.formula(model_LBMB), 
                         data = data, REML = T)),
         anova = list(anova(fit)),
         levene = list(anova(lm(abs(residuals(fit))^2 ~ strain_name + bloc_month,
                                data=data))),
         normres = list(shapiro.test(residuals(fit))))
